\uc0\u55357 \u57080 
\f1\b  ULTIMATE DRONE OS: TECHNICAL & OPERATOR MANUAL\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 System Version:
\f2\b0  V1.0 (Headless / Dual-MCU Architecture)\

\f1\b Target Hardware:
\f2\b0  Raspberry Pi (Master), Arduino Uno (Drive MCU), ESP8266 (Steer MCU)\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 1. SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE & DESIGN OVERVIEW\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs24 \cf0 The Ultimate Drone OS is a robust, web-based teleoperation platform designed for high-speed RC vehicles. It uses a distributed, three-brain architecture to ensure safety, low latency, and hardware protection.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The Master Brain (Raspberry Pi):
\f2\b0  Runs a Python Flask web server, processes camera/audio feeds using FFmpeg, handles GPS telemetry, serves the HTML frontend, and routes internet traffic via FRP tunneling.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Drive Controller (Arduino Uno):
\f2\b0  Dedicated exclusively to handling traction (ESC control via PWM), voltage/current sensor monitoring, ratcheted battery percentage calculations, hardware dead-time failsafes, and the physical TM1637 4-digit display.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Steer Controller (ESP8266):
\f2\b0  Dedicated to high-speed servo steering, maintaining "Iron Wall" physical travel limits, and enforcing anti-rollover speed constraints based on live GPS data.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 2. FIRST-TIME SETUP & WHAT TO EXPECT\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 Initial Boot Sequence\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2\b0\fs24 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Supply power to the Raspberry Pi and both microcontrollers.\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The Pi takes approximately 45-60 seconds to boot the OS, initialize the Apache proxy, and start the background services.\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
If the Pi cannot find a known Wi-Fi network within 50 seconds, it will automatically broadcast an emergency fallback hotspot.\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Connect your phone or laptop to the Wi-Fi network DRONE_SETUP using the password drone1234.\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Navigate your browser to the Pi's IP address (usually http://10.42.0.1 on the hotspot, or its assigned IP on a home network).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 First Load Calibration\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\fs24 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Legal Waiver:
\f2\b0  On the very first load, the HUD will prompt a legal waiver acknowledging the dangers of high-speed operation. You must accept this to unlock the UI.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
USB Binding:
\f2\b0  The system will display a loading spinner as it automatically pings /dev/ttyUSB* and /dev/ttyACM* to identify which port is the Uno and which is the ESP8266 based on their hardcoded IDs.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Battery Seed Prompt:
\f2\b0  The UI will ask for your current battery percentage. Entering this value seeds the "Smart Battery Ratchet" algorithm so it can accurately calculate voltage sag going forward.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

