\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 6. TESTING SERIAL COMMANDS VIA SSH (DIRECT MCU COMMUNICATION)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs24 \cf0 If you need to manually test commands (like setting the max steering walls) directly over SSH without the Python web server interfering, you must bypass the drone-pilot service.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Step 1: Stop the Python Backend\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs24 \cf0 The Python script constantly polls the USB ports. You must stop it so you can take control of the serial line.\
sudo systemctl stop drone-pilot\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Step 2: Identify Your USB Ports\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs24 \cf0 Find out which port the ESP8266 (Steering) and Uno (Drive) are connected to.\
ls /dev/ttyUSB* /dev/ttyACM*\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Step 3: Connect via Screen\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs24 \cf0 Use the screen utility to open a direct serial monitor to the ESP8266. Assuming the ESP8266 is on /dev/ttyUSB1:\
screen /dev/ttyUSB1 115200\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f3\i \cf0 Note: Once inside screen, whatever you type is sent directly to the MCU. Press Enter to send the command.
\f2\i0 \

\f3\i To exit screen, press Ctrl+A, then press K, then press Y.
\f2\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

